[{"id":41176,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$398 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$520 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$499 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$","$532 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{rms}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{3 \\rho \\mathrm{v}}{\\text { mass of the gas }}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41090,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>n</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For a gas having degrees of freedom&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and using Mayer&#39;s relation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi></math>. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41148,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math><mo>~</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mo>~</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mo>~</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mo>~</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Average collision rate <math><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mover accent=\"true\"><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mo>-</mo></mover><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#960;</mi></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6.023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>23</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>0.3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41138,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>11</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>R</mi><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41089,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> only</p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math> only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The rms velocity of a gas is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>rms</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><mi>M</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math>. Therefore,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>rms</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;independent of number of moles, Hence, statement A is correct&nbsp;and D is incorrect.</p><p>According to the ideal gas equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>n</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, statement B is correct and C is incorrect.</p><p>Ans&nbsp;[<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> only are correct]</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41191,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["80 K","73 K","3 K","20 K"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{v}_{\\mathrm{ms}} \\alpha \\sqrt{\\mathrm{T} / \\mathrm{m}} ; \\quad \\sqrt{\\frac{273+47}{32}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{T}{2}}$ or $\\mathrm{T}=20 \\mathrm{~K}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":41164,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$1.3 \\times 10^4$","$1.3 \\times 10^5$","$1.3 \\times 10^2$","$1.3 \\times 10^3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\nv &=\\sqrt{3 k_{\\mathrm{B}} T / m_{\\mathrm{He}}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{3 \\times 1.4 \\times 10^{-23} \\times 300}{7 \\times 10^{-27}}} \\\\\n&=1.34 \\times 10^3 \\mathrm{~m} / \\mathrm{s}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":41061,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>∞</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4c085d90-f6f0-4a5e-b68e-ff6a65779362.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 256px;\"/></p><p>For process <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>γ</mi><mi>log</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>V</mi><mi>γ</mi></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><msup><mi>V</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>γ</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo></math> Constant</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>γ</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo>…</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Likewise, for process <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>P</mi><msup><mi>V</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo></math> Constant</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo>…</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Also, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><mo> </mo><mo>…</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>By <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced></math>, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>P</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>v</mi></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41046,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\lambda=\\frac{\\mathrm{RT}}{\\sqrt{2} \\pi \\mathrm{d}^2 \\mathrm{~N}_{\\mathrm{A}} \\mathrm{P}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{KE}=\\frac{\\mathrm{f}}{2} \\mathrm{nRT}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41188,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$\\frac{4}{3}$","2","$\\frac{5}{3}$","$\\frac{3}{2}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{P} \\propto \\mathrm{T}^3 \\quad\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1}{\\mathrm{P}_2}\\right)=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{T}_1}{\\mathrm{~T}_2}\\right)^3$\nComparing it with standard eq. $\\frac{\\mathrm{C}_{\\mathrm{p}}}{\\mathrm{C}_{\\mathrm{v}}}=\\gamma=\\frac{3}{2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":41123,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;is false but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> is true.","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> is true but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> is false.","Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> are true.","Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math> and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math> are false."],"answer":1,"solution":"The translational kinetic energy &amp; rotational kinetic energy both obey Maxwell&#39;s distribution<br />independent of each other.<br />Translational kinetic energy of diatomic molecules <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>kT</mi></math><br />Rotational kinetic energy of diatomic molecules <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>kT</mi></math><br />So statement I is true but statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41128,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msqrt></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mrow><mi>mean</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mi>&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mi>T</mi></msqrt></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>V</mi><mi>N</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41084,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>According to Kinetic theory,&nbsp;</p><p>Average&nbsp;kinetic energy&nbsp;of a gas molecule&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msubsup><mi>v</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>k</mi><mi>T</mi></math></p><p>Thus,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>rms</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>k</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><mi>m</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p>At NTP,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>293</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p>Putting the values, we have</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>38</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>23</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>293</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>17</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41187,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{T}_1+\\mathrm{T}_2$","$\\left(\\mathrm{T}_1+\\mathrm{T}_2\\right) / 2$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{T}_1 \\mathrm{~T}_2\\left(\\mathrm{P}_1 \\mathrm{~V}_1+\\mathrm{P}_2 \\mathrm{~V}_2\\right)}{\\mathrm{P}_1 \\mathrm{~V}_1 \\mathrm{~T}_2+\\mathrm{P}_2 \\mathrm{~V}_2 \\mathrm{~T}_1}$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{T}_1 \\mathrm{~T}_2\\left(\\mathrm{P}_1 \\mathrm{~V}_1+\\mathrm{P}_2 \\mathrm{~V}_2\\right)}{\\mathrm{P}_1 \\mathrm{~V}_1 \\mathrm{~T}_1+\\mathrm{P}_2 \\mathrm{~T}_2 \\mathrm{~T}_2}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41157,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$15 \\%$","$30 \\%$","$25 \\%$","$20 \\%$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Assume final temperature $=\\mathrm{T}^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$ Heat lass $=$ Heat gain $=\\mathrm{ms} \\Delta \\mathrm{T}$ $\\Rightarrow \\mathrm{m}_{\\mathrm{B}} \\mathrm{s}_{\\mathrm{B}} \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\mathrm{m}_{\\mathrm{w}} \\mathrm{s}_{\\mathrm{w}} \\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{w}}$\r\n\r\n$0.1 \\times 400 \\times(500-\\mathrm{T})$\r\n\r\n$\\quad=0.5 \\times 4200 \\times(\\mathrm{T}-30)+800(\\mathrm{~T}-30)$\r\n\r\n$\\Rightarrow 40(500-\\mathrm{T})=(\\mathrm{T}-30)(2100+800)$\r\n\r\n$\\Rightarrow 20000-40 \\mathrm{~T}=2900 \\mathrm{~T}-30 \\times 2900$\r\n\r\n$\\Rightarrow 20000+30 \\times 2900=\\mathrm{T}(2940)$\r\n\r\n$\\mathrm{T}=30.4^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$\r\n\r\n$\\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{T}}{\\mathrm{T}} \\times 100=\\frac{6.4}{30} \\times 100=21 \\%$\r\n\r\nso the closest answer is $20 \\%$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41137,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math>and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>As we know mean free path</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mfenced><mfrac><mi>N</mi><mi>V</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>N = no. of molecule</p><p>V = volume of container</p><p>d = diameter of molecule</p><p>Velocity constant and no. of molecules are same. So mean free path remains same. As temperature increases no. of collision increases so relaxation time decrease.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41070,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>551</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>651</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>451</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>751</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the rms speed of the argon molecules is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><msub><mi>M</mi><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></mfrac></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>The formula to calculate the rms speed of chlorine molecule is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><msub><mi>M</mi><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow></msub></mfrac></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Divide equation (1) by equation (2) and simplify to obtain the required ratio.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>Ar</mi></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>Cl</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>M</mi><mi>Cl</mi></msub><msub><mi>M</mi><mi>Ar</mi></msub></mfrac></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>3</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameters into equation (3) and solve to calculate the required value.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>Ar</mi></msub><mrow><mn>490</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><msqrt><mfrac><mn>71</mn><mn>40</mn></mfrac></msqrt></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><msub><mi>v</mi><mrow><mi>A</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>71</mn><mn>40</mn></mfrac></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>490</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8776;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>651</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41036,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$P_{B}=P_{A}$","$P_{B}=P_{A} \\exp \\left(M \\omega^{2} l^{2} / 3 R T\\right)$","$P_{B}=P_{A} \\exp \\left(M \\omega^{2} l^{2} / R T\\right)$","$P_{B}=P_{A} \\exp \\left(M \\omega^{2} l^{2} / 2 R T\\right)$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<br>$A[(P + dP) - P] = (dm)(\\omega^2 x)$<br>$dP = \\dfrac{(dm)}{A} \\omega^2 x$<br>$dP = \\dfrac{(\\rho)(A)(dx)\\omega^2 x}{A}$<br>also $[PM = \\rho RT]$<br>$\\rho = \\dfrac{PM}{RT}$<br>$dP = \\left( \\dfrac{PM}{RT} \\right) \\omega^2 x \\, dx$<br>$\\int_{P_A}^{P_B} \\dfrac{dP}{P} = \\dfrac{\\omega^2 M}{RT} \\int_{0}^{\\ell} x \\, dx$<br>$\\ln \\left( \\dfrac{P_B}{P_A} \\right) = \\dfrac{\\omega^2 \\ell^2 M}{2RT}$<br>$P_B = P_A e^{\\dfrac{M\\omega^2 \\ell^2}{2RT}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41037,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["-235","-253","-100","-20"],"answer":1,"solution":"The root-mean-square speed of gas molecules is: $v_{rms} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3RT}{M}}$, where $T$ is absolute temperature and $M$ is molar mass.<br><br>For oxygen at $T_1 = 47°C = 320$ K with $M_{O_2} = 32$ g/mol:<br>$v_{rms,O_2} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3R(320)}{32}}$<br><br>For hydrogen with $M_{H_2} = 2$ g/mol at temperature $T_2$:<br>$v_{rms,H_2} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3RT_2}{2}}$<br><br>Equating the RMS speeds:<br>$\\sqrt{\\frac{3R(320)}{32}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{3RT_2}{2}}$<br><br>$\\frac{320}{32} = \\frac{T_2}{2}$<br><br>$T_2 = 2 \\times 10 = 20$ K<br><br>Converting to Celsius: $t_2 = 20 - 273 = -253°C$, which is option (2).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41092,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>72</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>32</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>54</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Number of moles of Hydrogen <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>m</mi><mi>M</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>16</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p>Number of moles of oxygen&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>128</mn><mn>32</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>Using ideal gas equation,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math>,</p><p>Where pressure&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Pa</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>STP</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Putting the values,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>314</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>273</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>314</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>273</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41178,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["Statement-1 is false and Statement-2 is true.","Statement-1 and Statement-2 both are true. \nStatement-2 is the correct explanation of Statement-1.","Statement-1 is true and Statement- 2 is false.","Statement-1 and Statement-2 both are true. \nStatement-2 is not correct explanation of Statement-1."],"answer":0,"solution":"In ideal gases the molecules are considered as point particles and for point particles, there is no internal excitation, no vibration and no rotation. For an ideal gas the internal energy can only be translational kinetic energy and for real gas both kinetic as well as potential energy.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41067,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>39</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>39</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the average kinetic energy per molecule of a gas at any temperature&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>T</mi></math>&nbsp;is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>avg</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mi>T</mi></math></p><p>where,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>B</mi></msub></math>&nbsp;is Boltzmann constant.</p><p>From above equation, it can be concluded that the average kinetic energy per molecule is independent of the molecular weight of the gas.</p><p>Hence, the required ratio is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41054,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$f_t=2$ and $f_r=2$","$f_t=3$ and $f_r=3$","$f_t=3$ and $f_r=2$","$f_t=2$ and $f_r=3$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Since $\\mathrm{CH}_4$ is polyatomic Non-Linear\nD.O.F of $\\mathrm{CH}_4$\nT. DOF $=3$\n$\\mathrm{RDOF}=3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41143,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1.45</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.50</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.47</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.42</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Let $n_1,n_2$ be the number of moles of gases $1$ and $2$.<br>We have $\\dfrac{C_{p_1}}{C_{v_1}}=\\dfrac{5}{3}$ and We know $C_{p_1}=C_{v_1}+R$<br>$\\therefore \\dfrac{5C_{v_1}}{3}=C_{v_1}+R,\\dfrac{2C_{v_1}}{3}R_1,C_{v_1}=\\dfrac{3R}{2}$<br>$A$ and $C_{p_1}=C_{ v_ 1 }+R=\\dfrac{5R}{2}$<br>Also, $\\dfrac{C_{ p_ 2}}{C_{ v_ 2 }}=\\dfrac{4}{3}$ and<br>$C_{p_2}=C_{v_2}+R$<br>$\\therefore \\dfrac{4C_{ v_ 2 }}{3}=C_{ v_ 2 }+R, \\dfrac{C_{ v_ 2 }}{3}=R,C_{ v_ 2 }=3R$<br>$C_{ p_ 2}=C_{ v_ 2 }+ R=4R$<br>Now $C_{ v_ {mix} }=\\dfrac{n_1C_{ v_ 1 }+n_2C_{ v_ 2 }}{n_1+n_2}=\\dfrac{2\\times \\dfrac{3R}{2}+3\\times 3R}{2+3}$<br>$=\\dfrac{3R+9R}{5}=\\dfrac{12R}{5}$<br>$C_{ p_ {mix} }=\\dfrac{n_1C_{ p_ 1 }+n_2C_{ p_ 2 }}{n_1+n_2}=\\dfrac{2\\times \\dfrac{5R}{2}+3\\times 4R}{2+3}$<br>$=\\dfrac{17R}{5}$<br>$l_{mix}=\\dfrac{C_{ p_ {mix} }}{C_{ v_ {mix} }}=\\dfrac{17}{12}=1.4166=1.42$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41051,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$\\frac{5}{3}$","$\\frac{9}{7}$","$\\frac{3}{2}$","$\\frac{7}{5}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{P} \\propto \\mathrm{T}^3 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{PT}^{-3}=\\text { constant } \\\\\n& \\because \\frac{\\mathrm{PV}}{\\mathrm{T}}=\\mathrm{nR}=\\text { constant from ideal gas equation } \\\\\n& (\\mathrm{P})(\\mathrm{PV})^{-3}=\\text { constant } \\\\\n& \\mathrm{P}^{-2} \\mathrm{~V}^{-3}=\\text { cosntant }...(i)\n\\end{aligned}$\n$\\because$ Process equation for adiabatic process is\n$\\mathrm{PV}^{\\mathrm{y}}=\\text { constant }...(ii)$\nComparing equation (1) and (2)\n$\\frac{C_P}{C_V}=y=\\frac{3}{2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41073,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>11</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>16</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The internal energy of a gas is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><msub><mi>C</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mi>T</mi></math>.</p><p>A diatomic gas has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;translational and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;rotational degrees of freedom. A monoatomic gas has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;translational degrees of freedom.</p><p>Hence, the internal energy of the mixture&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>C</mi><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msub><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>C</mi><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mi>T</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>T</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41158,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$15 \\mathrm{RT}$","$12 \\mathrm{RT}$","$4 \\mathrm{RT}$","$20 \\mathrm{RT}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$U=\\frac{f_{1}}{2} n_{1} R T+\\frac{f_{2}}{2} n_{2} R T$\r\n\r\nConsidering translational and rotational modes, degrees of freedom $\\mathrm{f}_{1}=5$ and $\\mathrm{f}_{2}=3$ $\\therefore \\mathrm{u}=\\frac{5}{2}(3 \\mathrm{RT})+\\frac{3}{2} \\times 5 \\mathrm{RT}$\r\n\r\n$\\mathrm{U}=15 \\mathrm{RT}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41140,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math><mn>7</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>9</mn></math>","<math><mn>5</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>9</mn></math>","<math><mn>3</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>5</mn></math>","<math><mn>5</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>7</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Molar heat capacity of <math><mi>A</mi></math> at constant volume <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/>Molar heat capacity of <math><mi>B</mi></math> at constant volume <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/>Dividing both <math><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41180,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["$\\frac{n_1 T_1+n_2 T_2+n_3 T_3}{n_1+n_2+n_3}$","$\\frac{n_1 T_1+n_2 T_2^2+n_3 T_3^2}{n_1 T_1+n_2 T_2+n_3 T_3}$","$\\frac{n_1^2 T_1^2+n_2^2 T_2^2+n_3^2 T_3^2}{n_1 T_1+n_2 T_2+n_3 T_3}$","$\\frac{\\left(T_1+T_2+T_3\\right)}{3}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Data $\\Rightarrow n, k, t_1+n_2 k T_2+n_3 k T_3=\\left(n_1+n_2+n_3\\right) k T$\n$\\therefore T=\\frac{n_1 T_1+n_2 T_2+n_3 T_3}{n_1+n_2+n_3}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":41065,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Kinetic Theory of Gases","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6845</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5942</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6232</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5670</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The formula to calculate the kinetic energy can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>n</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Since oxygen is a diatomic gas, the number of degrees of freedom is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>.</p><p>Thus, from equation (1), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>K</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>31</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>300</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>6232</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]